00:56.056 --> 01:00.357
Truth is I love it,
the Formula 1 stuff, the real stuff,

01:00.435 --> 01:02.984
the speed they're going
through the corners,

01:03.063 --> 01:06.567
it's super men so I really believe
these guys meta morph

01:06.650 --> 01:08.493
when they get into the cockpit you know.

01:08.569 --> 01:12.574
They're immensely quick,
and the grip round the corners

01:12.656 --> 01:13.532
is just astonishing.

01:51.278 --> 01:54.327
<i>If you're</i> a <i>pilot flying</i> a <i>jet,</i>

01:54.406 --> 01:56.704
that's wonderful work isn't it? Why?

01:56.742 --> 01:59.416
Because I'm flying supersonic,
twice supersonic.

02:01.788 --> 02:06.089
<i>It blows my mind, the speeds
at which they can control these cars.</i>

02:08.669 --> 02:12.220
<i>What was it, Top Gun,
what did Mav say to Goose?</i>

02:12.299 --> 02:15.849
He said “I feel the need,
the need for speed",

02:15.927 --> 02:17.725
I've never forgotten that.

02:17.804 --> 02:19.490
- And you've always had that?
- Sorry?

02:19.514 --> 02:20.908
You've always had that?

02:20.932 --> 02:22.243
Well I've always been
a little boy for a start,

02:22.267 --> 02:24.440
always enjoyed speed too.

02:24.519 --> 02:26.738
That's why I finished up in a chair,
going too fast.

02:31.109 --> 02:32.795
<i>We didn't sit round
the table as</i> a <i>family</i>

02:32.819 --> 02:35.006
<i>and discuss it and go
this is how we're gonna deal with it</i>

02:35.030 --> 02:36.657
<i>or you know
mum needs some counselling,</i>

02:36.740 --> 02:40.540
<i>the kids need counselling,
dad needs counselling to get through it.</i>

02:40.619 --> 02:44.795
We've never talked about it
<i>as</i> a family, dad's accident, ever.

03:11.108 --> 03:13.782
<i>If it wasn't for Mum
I personally don't think.</i>

03:13.860 --> 03:16.704
<i>Williams would necessarily be around.</i>

03:16.780 --> 03:21.331
I'm a really firm believer in Williams
is not just always about Dad,

03:21.410 --> 03:22.957
it's <i>as</i> much about Mum,

03:23.036 --> 03:28.088
<i>she stood by him through thick and thin,
I mean she saved his life.</i>

04:32.564 --> 04:34.566
<i>Williams is unique now</i>

04:34.649 --> 04:37.823
<i>in that it is
the last of the old style teams</i>

04:37.861 --> 04:41.491
where the team owners
all had their name over the door

04:41.573 --> 04:43.325
and Williams is the only one left.

04:45.327 --> 04:47.054
<i>Frank's very rare
at interviews nowadays</i>

04:47.078 --> 04:49.126
<i>so he doesn't seem as
approachable or accessible</i>

04:49.206 --> 04:50.583
<i>from a, from a fan on the street.</i>

04:50.665 --> 04:52.542
Whether we see enough
of him nowadays

04:52.626 --> 04:54.799
and whether
that's because of his health...

04:54.878 --> 04:55.800
We didn't see him this weekend,

04:55.879 --> 04:57.973
we saw Claire Williams
knocking about on Friday.

04:58.048 --> 05:00.426
<i>She's a great face on the TV as well,</i>

05:00.509 --> 05:02.352
<i>where, you know being interviewed
and the like,</i>

05:02.427 --> 05:05.431
it's interesting to have
a lady <i>as</i> Principal as well.

05:14.773 --> 05:17.151
<i>I think I may have
had like the odd grand dream</i>

05:17.234 --> 05:21.114
but I never thought I would be given
the keys to the shop ever, ever, ever.

05:22.531 --> 05:25.501
I think a bit of it's because
I'm a girl and you know

05:25.575 --> 05:28.044
I can't possibly understand
anything about a car

05:28.119 --> 05:30.542
and you know it's Dad's train set

05:30.580 --> 05:33.049
and he doesn't wanna
hand it over to anybody else.

05:33.124 --> 05:34.764
<i>The Marussia of Will Stevens</i>

05:34.793 --> 05:37.216
<i>gets out the way of Valtteri Bottas
and Max Verstappen</i>

05:37.295 --> 05:39.514
<i>but Verstappen's all over
the back of that Williams.</i>

05:41.174 --> 05:42.485
What about Williams?
Where do you reckon

05:42.509 --> 05:43.761
Williams will place today?

05:43.844 --> 05:49.271
Uh... might get a point.
One of the top ten maybe.

05:49.349 --> 05:51.244
Do you think they're
contenders anymore?

05:51.268 --> 05:54.397
No, no.
Definitely not this year. No chance.

05:58.525 --> 06:00.823
But Jacques,
you were the last driver

06:00.861 --> 06:03.614
to win a World Championship
for Williams.

06:03.697 --> 06:04.897
Yeah that's true, that's true.

06:04.948 --> 06:10.500
- How long ago was that?
- Uh... '97 so 20 years ago.

06:10.579 --> 06:12.172
- Yes.
- Long time.

06:12.247 --> 06:14.045
Too long really, yeah.

06:14.124 --> 06:17.719
<i>In comes Bottas,
goes for another set,</i>

06:17.794 --> 06:19.730
<i>he's just given up,
there's nothing they can do really</i>

06:19.754 --> 06:21.973
<i>and I'm afraid that Williams
are gonna come away</i>

06:22.048 --> 06:24.642
<i>from Monaco with nothing.</i>

06:27.512 --> 06:28.934
<i>It's really frustrating,</i>

06:29.014 --> 06:33.064
<i>it literally is banging your head against
a brick wall, what do we have to do?</i>

06:33.101 --> 06:35.399
You know I have to walk around
with my head held high

06:35.478 --> 06:39.733
and I want to be able to do that um
and I don't feel that I can at the moment.

06:39.816 --> 06:42.990
Do you think Frank feels it
as acutely as you do now?

06:43.069 --> 06:45.322
I'm sure he does,
he's trusted in me

06:45.405 --> 06:48.659
and I don't want him to ever doubt
that trust that he's put in me.

06:49.951 --> 06:52.170
Do you ever doubt it
yourself or...

06:52.245 --> 06:58.002
Um not right now no,
I've got a lot of fight in me left.

06:59.461 --> 07:02.260
<i>Claire is</i> a <i>tough piece of work,</i>

07:02.339 --> 07:05.388
<i>whatever she sets out to do
she always achieves it,</i>

07:05.467 --> 07:07.720
she's a bit like her mother,
her mother was like that,

07:07.802 --> 07:10.225
didn't make a lot of fuss,
just did things.

07:14.684 --> 07:17.187
<i>I love this time of the year
with the Autumn coming.</i>

07:17.270 --> 07:19.443
These are my mum's blossom trees
that we planted.

07:19.522 --> 07:21.524
They look a bit dead now.

07:21.608 --> 07:23.986
These were the ones that we
planted on her,

07:24.069 --> 07:27.118
the anniversary, two year anniversary
of her passing.

07:27.197 --> 07:30.997
I wanted something here
that I could come to and chat to.

07:31.076 --> 07:33.625
- And do you do that?
- Yeah I do, a lot.

07:36.915 --> 07:40.340
I come and ask her why
we can't fix our um,

07:40.418 --> 07:44.423
the wheel nuts on our pit stops
and pray to her that

07:44.506 --> 07:46.304
she might help the guys in R&D

07:46.341 --> 07:48.469
that have been working
so hard on them.

07:51.554 --> 07:52.554
Right.

07:54.849 --> 07:56.977
I've got a whole box of
press clippings in there

07:57.060 --> 07:59.563
from when I was made
Deputy Team Principal.

07:59.646 --> 08:01.865
I thought I would frame them
and put them up

08:01.940 --> 08:05.820
and be all proud of myself, but now
they've just ended up in the shed.

08:15.161 --> 08:17.664
This is a lovely picture
from when we won

08:17.747 --> 08:19.499
the race in Barcelona with Pastor.

08:19.541 --> 08:21.760
Was this the last time
you won a race?

08:21.835 --> 08:24.634
Last time we won a race,
Barcelona 2012.

08:24.713 --> 08:27.341
So there's another picture of dad,
someone sent that to me,

08:27.424 --> 08:32.851
it's amazing, him lifting two wheel nuts,
how buff was my dad? It's amazing.

08:32.929 --> 08:36.775
It's was phenomenal how fit he
was before his accident.

08:36.850 --> 08:41.447
Oh this is an awful article that came out
when mum did an extract from her book.

08:43.565 --> 08:44.583
After the accident,

08:44.607 --> 08:46.951
I think Ginny was
on the edge of a nervous breakdown

08:47.027 --> 08:49.746
and she found communication,

08:49.779 --> 08:51.873
on an emotional level,
very difficult with Frank,

08:51.948 --> 08:53.245
Frank didn't do emotion

08:53.324 --> 08:55.747
and she perhaps felt that

08:55.827 --> 09:01.459
a book might be one way of
getting the story across to him.

09:07.839 --> 09:10.934
"I'm not usually given
to making New Year's resolutions"

09:11.009 --> 09:15.185
but at the end of 1988 I decided that
I would spend the following year

09:15.221 --> 09:18.065
setting down everything
that has happened to Frank and me

09:18.099 --> 09:19.521
"in the last two decades."

09:26.733 --> 09:28.531
Yes.

09:35.992 --> 09:42.170
These are the little micro tapes that,
they took about 6 hours of conversation.

09:44.084 --> 09:47.714
That goes in... there.

10:03.895 --> 10:05.873
How long is it
since you listened to these?

10:05.897 --> 10:09.572
Probably not since
I first transcribed them, which, so it is,

10:09.651 --> 10:13.781
<i>it's 25 years ago and
I mean she sounds so alive today,</i>

10:13.822 --> 10:16.871
25 years later
I can relieve that conversation.

10:18.743 --> 10:22.418
<i>I feel very sad that
she's not here anymore.</i>

10:35.093 --> 10:36.320
- Hello Pamela.
- Hello...

10:36.344 --> 10:37.863
- How are you?
- No need to ask who you are.

10:37.887 --> 10:40.060
I feel I should hug you
or kiss you or something.

10:40.140 --> 10:42.108
- Oh!
- I feel I know you so well already.

10:42.183 --> 10:44.537
Well looking at you...
I feel I know you so, really yes.

10:44.561 --> 10:45.437
Is it a bit weird.

10:45.520 --> 10:47.720
- It is weird yes.
- Really? Do I look like mum?

10:47.772 --> 10:49.820
You do.

10:50.733 --> 10:52.373
<i>It was so weird
because I didn't,</i>

10:52.402 --> 10:54.325
<i>she obviously didn't tell
anyone in the family,</i>

10:54.404 --> 10:57.658
<i>but there was all this kind
of quite suspicious behaviour going on,</i>

10:57.740 --> 11:01.119
<i>kind of sneaking out or you know
I find the Dictaphone in her glove box.</i>

11:01.202 --> 11:03.722
I was convinced she was having
an affair and confronted her with it

11:03.746 --> 11:06.670
and she still didn't tell me that
that's what she was doing.

11:39.240 --> 11:41.242
She actually met Frank

11:41.326 --> 11:44.375
about three months
before she was due to get married

11:44.454 --> 11:47.207
and that her fiancé
introduced her to Frank

11:47.290 --> 11:50.260
and there was an instant sort of
electric connection

11:50.335 --> 11:52.178
between her and Frank,

11:52.253 --> 11:54.722
she was only, I think 20,
she was very young

11:54.797 --> 11:56.219
and she thought, “What can I do?

11:56.299 --> 11:59.519
"The flowers are ordered,
the wedding oh..."

12:18.905 --> 12:24.332
Well she was blonde, blue eyes,
beautiful thick head of hair,

12:24.410 --> 12:27.505
<i>beautiful manners, beautiful clothes,
came from quite a wealthy background.</i>

12:28.665 --> 12:31.259
<i>She had
this lovely way of speaking.</i>

12:31.334 --> 12:32.460
<i>Great sense of humour.</i>

12:32.543 --> 12:35.137
And she loved motor racing,
she understood motor racing.

12:35.213 --> 12:37.591
She had a very good feel
for racing drivers.

12:39.550 --> 12:41.528
<i>Frank probably thought
you're not gonna believe it,</i>

12:41.552 --> 12:43.600
<i>she went to a finishing
school in Switzerland,</i>

12:43.680 --> 12:46.980
they've got Labradors
in the garden, I've cracked it.

12:47.058 --> 12:49.857
<i>I suspect that's what he told his mates.</i>

12:49.936 --> 12:52.189
I mean she was just
a fantastic girl to talk to,

12:52.272 --> 12:55.947
it was like talking to a fella,
but you know with, wearing Chanel No. 5

12:56.025 --> 12:57.025
it was just brilliant.

12:57.860 --> 13:00.329
But in <i>those</i> days,
to back out of a marriage

13:00.405 --> 13:03.409
or a looming wedding was
almost impossible to do,

13:03.491 --> 13:05.664
you know invitations had
gone out and stuff like that

13:05.743 --> 13:11.546
and it would've been very tough
for her to, to pull the plug on it.

13:11.624 --> 13:13.102
Anyway she went through with
the wedding

13:13.126 --> 13:16.175
but this attraction didn't go away.

13:16.254 --> 13:19.098
It was the charm,
it was the Frank William's charm I think,

13:19.173 --> 13:24.896
that smile and the big green eyes
and mum just went loony.

13:25.722 --> 13:27.116
<i>You know,
I remember going to cross</i> a <i>road</i>

13:27.140 --> 13:28.858
<i>and she's sitting in a Mini car,</i>

13:28.933 --> 13:30.035
<i>I said, “What you doing here?”</i>

13:30.059 --> 13:32.061
<i>"She said
“Brode, don't say anything to anybody"</i>

13:32.145 --> 13:35.991
and she had a flask and sandwiches and
she'd been sitting there from nine o'clock

13:36.065 --> 13:38.989
hoping Frank would go across the road
and buy a paper at the newsagents

13:39.068 --> 13:40.170
and she could get out and say.

13:40.194 --> 13:43.164
"Oh Frank,
fancy bumping into you here"

13:43.239 --> 13:46.083
and she didn't do it once,
she did it all week.

14:14.103 --> 14:18.233
It was a real magical
world, the world Frank started racing,

14:18.316 --> 14:21.866
<i>it was this, you know, boys club
and I think Frank,</i>

14:21.944 --> 14:24.447
<i>he loved being a part of it,
and maybe because</i>

14:24.530 --> 14:27.784
<i>he hadn't been a part of a,
a gang, a group</i>

14:27.867 --> 14:30.120
<i>when he was you know in his childhood.</i>

14:44.717 --> 14:47.561
<i>My father left, he was</i>
a <i>bomber pilot, left my mother.</i>

14:47.637 --> 14:49.480
<i>My mother brought me up.</i>

14:49.555 --> 14:52.149
<i>She did bring me up
pretty much single-handedly.</i>

14:52.225 --> 14:55.229
<i>They lived in
Jarrow in South Shields,</i>

14:55.311 --> 14:57.029
<i>that was a difficult environment,</i>

14:57.105 --> 15:02.362
<i>difficult to make your way out of
and my grandma made the choice,</i>

15:02.443 --> 15:06.368
she would sacrifice
the normal home environment

15:06.447 --> 15:09.166
in order to try and give dad
a better chance in life

15:09.242 --> 15:10.869
by giving him this education.

15:14.163 --> 15:16.211
<i>My first memories
were being sent to</i>

15:16.290 --> 15:20.170
a <i>Roman Catholic convent,
I was about, just coming up for five</i>

15:20.253 --> 15:21.939
<i>and I used to run away at
the railway station</i>

15:21.963 --> 15:23.690
<i>and they used to ring up
and say he's here again,</i>

15:23.714 --> 15:25.261
<i>please stop this happening again,</i>

15:25.299 --> 15:27.444
whenever I got back, the school
they took my little trousers down

15:27.468 --> 15:29.937
and hit me with a, a coat hanger.

15:31.222 --> 15:33.850
I didn't mind,
I was quite happy at the school.

15:33.933 --> 15:36.578
- You were happy at school?
- I was happy at the school, yes.

15:36.602 --> 15:37.955
So, and why did
you run away then?

15:37.979 --> 15:40.232
Uh... because
I wasn't that happy.

15:40.314 --> 15:44.194
No, but it was, I also loved trains,
I love trains and movement,

15:44.277 --> 15:45.957
<i>I was always trying
to get a ride in a car,</i>

15:45.987 --> 15:47.881
<i>you know when someone's dad
turned up with a car,</i>

15:47.905 --> 15:48.747
<i>I was all over the car</i>

15:48.781 --> 15:50.843
<i>and sometimes they gave me
a ride up and down the road in it.</i>

15:50.867 --> 15:52.619
<i>I was, I was nuts about cars by then.</i>

16:04.297 --> 16:06.316
<i>I did qualify for uni
but I had no interest,</i>

16:06.340 --> 16:09.640
because I was uh... in a convent for
three years, one year at a day school,

16:09.719 --> 16:11.596
then another nine years
locked up as well,

16:11.679 --> 16:13.306
I was kind of keen on freedom.

16:17.059 --> 16:20.905
I'd bought for £80 a racing A35,

16:20.980 --> 16:23.733
it was a hot little ship I can tell you,
very quick car

16:24.901 --> 16:27.199
<i>and that's how I got into
motor racing proper.</i>

16:28.362 --> 16:31.457
He was totally
obsessed by motor racing.

16:31.532 --> 16:34.957
<i>I mean, to a degree
that was ridiculous. Ridiculous.</i>

16:35.036 --> 16:36.036
<i>Nothing else mattered.</i>

16:36.078 --> 16:39.048
I don't think he's ever been
in a supermarket in his life.

16:49.091 --> 16:50.444
Frank, when he first went there,

16:50.468 --> 16:52.362
<i>there wasn't any room for him
so he slept in the lock ups</i>

16:52.386 --> 16:55.265
<i>down the side there in a sleeping bag.</i>

16:57.642 --> 16:58.985
<i>Everybody had a nickname.</i>

16:59.060 --> 17:02.985
<i>Roger Bunting was Bunt,
Charles Lucas was Charlie Luke,</i>

17:03.022 --> 17:07.823
Piers Courage was called Porridge,
and Franks was called Wanks.

17:07.859 --> 17:11.830
Ah is Wanks around?
No he'll be in later.

17:11.906 --> 17:12.748
Oh okay.

17:12.781 --> 17:16.457
They were all
aristocratic, wealthy guys

17:16.536 --> 17:20.632
who wanted to go motor racing
and Frank was mixing with them.

17:20.705 --> 17:22.674
And he wasn't either
aristocratic or wealthy.

17:31.259 --> 17:33.659
Well, all the other guys
that live in that flat

17:33.719 --> 17:38.065
had hereditary incomes.
Frank didn't, nor did I,

17:38.140 --> 17:39.642
<i>so Frank had to earn some money.</i>

17:39.725 --> 17:43.229
<i>So the way he earned money
was to buy and sell parts.</i>

17:43.312 --> 17:46.566
<i>And every waking moment
he was chasing around the country</i>

17:46.649 --> 17:49.493
<i>buying stuff for a pound
and selling it for 2 pound.</i>

17:49.569 --> 17:52.664
<i>He called himself Frank Williams
Racing Cars in the end.</i>

17:52.738 --> 17:54.285
The motivation behind the organisers

17:54.365 --> 17:57.960
wanting certain drivers was
that in France they had to have Matre,

17:58.035 --> 18:01.005
they had to have Beltoise
and Servoz-Gavin starting.

18:01.080 --> 18:03.333
Italy had to have a Ferrari on the grid.

18:03.416 --> 18:05.919
And I guess England
particularly wanted to be RM.

18:06.002 --> 18:09.927
He seemed to me to be
the ultimate wheeler dealer.

18:10.006 --> 18:12.555
And then he expanded
and expanded and pretty soon

18:12.633 --> 18:18.185
<i>he was selling a lot of cars
to European drivers particularly in Italy.</i>

18:18.222 --> 18:21.271
So Frank would get
a phone call from an Italian customer.

18:21.350 --> 18:22.786
<i>“Hey Franks,
what are you gonna give me</i>

18:22.810 --> 18:24.312
"for my car I need a new Brabham?"

18:24.395 --> 18:27.615
“I'll give you X for it."
“Okay, I'll come and get it."

18:27.690 --> 18:29.317
<i>He's got an order
from the same customer</i>

18:29.400 --> 18:31.198
<i>for a brand new car.</i>

18:31.277 --> 18:33.154
<i>He'd then take that car apart,</i>

18:33.237 --> 18:35.535
<i>repaint it,
re-electroplate it, re-polish it</i>

18:35.615 --> 18:40.621
and it would be, <i>3</i> months later, a totally
immaculate brand new looking car

18:40.661 --> 18:44.541
with a brand new chassis number
that he got out the back door at Brabham.

18:44.582 --> 18:46.584
The guy would then get the car back

18:46.667 --> 18:49.546
<i>and what he actually got back
was the original car.</i>

18:51.213 --> 18:55.389
I know one guy had the same car
for at least <i>3</i> years

18:55.468 --> 18:58.096
but he thought
he got a new car every year.

19:07.730 --> 19:11.325
<i>Ginny had grown up
in</i> a <i>very sheltered environment</i>

19:11.400 --> 19:15.280
and suddenly there was this man
who didn't go by the rules

19:15.363 --> 19:16.990
<i>and he was very exciting.</i>

19:21.827 --> 19:24.626
We'd go to parties on</i> a <i>Saturday night

19:24.705 --> 19:29.006
and Frank's dancing with Ginny
and it's getting obscene

19:29.085 --> 19:32.589
<i>and her husband has got
daggers coming out of his eyes</i>

19:32.672 --> 19:36.176
<i>"and I walked up to Frank and I said
“Frank, what the fuck are you doing?"</i>

19:36.258 --> 19:38.306
<i>I said you can't be doing this,
have a normal dance,</i>

19:38.386 --> 19:42.391
<i>I mean you know the only thing
he wasn't doing was having sex,</i>

19:42.473 --> 19:46.228
and Frank said, “Oh I hadn't noticed"
and Ginny said, “Well I certainly hadn't"

19:46.310 --> 19:48.688
but everybody else had.

19:49.647 --> 19:52.571
<i>And then of course the show
was on the road then with them two.</i>

19:52.650 --> 19:54.027
And she moved into a flat

19:54.110 --> 19:59.082
and then she thought,
“How do I let Frank know that I'm here?

19:59.156 --> 20:04.913
Because I mustn't let him know that I,
left my first husband because of him,

20:04.995 --> 20:06.014
"that would scare him off."

20:06.038 --> 20:10.509
<i>So he didn't drink but
what he loved was fresh orange juice,</i>

20:10.584 --> 20:12.632
<i>so she wrote a letter,</i>

20:12.712 --> 20:15.841
<i>'if you fancy some fresh orange
juice, it's now being served at... ',</i>

20:15.923 --> 20:18.642
and she put her new address
and a day or two later

20:18.718 --> 20:19.861
the doorbell rang

20:19.885 --> 20:21.512
and he turned up at the door.

20:21.595 --> 20:22.781
Looking for
some orange juice?

20:22.805 --> 20:26.605
Looking for some orange juice,
obviously.

20:28.644 --> 20:29.955
<i>And they're away...</i>

20:29.979 --> 20:31.957
<i>I saw Frank Williams
make</i> a <i>very good start from the back,</i>

20:31.981 --> 20:34.450
<i>he's now in third place
from about the third row of the grid,</i>

20:34.525 --> 20:35.617
<i>that's very good indeed.</i>

20:36.694 --> 20:37.879
<i>Back then his whole thing</i>

20:37.903 --> 20:39.871
<i>was to be
the greatest racing driver in the world.</i>

20:40.948 --> 20:42.592
<i>..who's the yellow car
sneaking through there?</i>

20:42.616 --> 20:43.458
<i>Frank Williams.</i>

20:43.534 --> 20:45.095
<i>It's Frank, look at him sneaking,</i>

20:45.119 --> 20:47.372
<i>what a battle with these two saloons.
My word...</i>

20:47.455 --> 20:49.457
He was racing saloon cars,

20:49.540 --> 20:50.507
<i>but for some reason,</i>

20:50.541 --> 20:51.685
<i>he never had an in built limit,</i>

20:51.709 --> 20:53.395
he would just go faster
and faster and faster

20:53.419 --> 20:54.420
and fly off the circuit.

20:54.462 --> 20:57.182
<i>- And who's off there?
- Frank Williams.</i>

20:57.214 --> 20:58.817
<i>Frank Williams trying too hard,</i>

20:58.841 --> 21:02.891
<i>Frank always very fast
but very hairy and he's living up to it.</i>

21:02.970 --> 21:05.018
When I started doing
uh... Formula 3

21:05.097 --> 21:07.600
sometimes I would encounter people
who would say to me

21:07.683 --> 21:09.310
do you know that chap Frank Williams?

21:09.393 --> 21:12.363
Yeah, I know Frank Williams,
oh, he's so fast and he,

21:12.438 --> 21:14.440
and he crashed here
and he overtook here

21:14.523 --> 21:15.775
and he did all kinds of things.

21:15.858 --> 21:20.159
<i>So Frank had this amazing reputation
as someone who was lightning fast,</i>

21:20.237 --> 21:22.114
<i>not always staying on the road.</i>

21:23.157 --> 21:24.926
<i>There were</i> a
<i>lot of races, he would've won,</i>

21:24.950 --> 21:27.078
<i>but he ended up spinning the car
and having accidents,</i>

21:27.161 --> 21:28.003
he just didn't have a limit

21:28.078 --> 21:30.376
and that extended
to his road driving as well.

21:30.456 --> 21:33.175
- Well what was that like?
- Diabolical.

21:35.920 --> 21:38.093
Where did you learn to drive?

21:38.172 --> 21:40.925
<i>In my mother's Morris 1000,</i>

21:41.008 --> 21:43.636
<i>she was very reluctant to lend it to me,</i>

21:43.719 --> 21:46.563
<i>and she was right because in the end
I did roll it on its roof.</i>

21:46.639 --> 21:48.408
But you rolled a few cars in your time.

21:48.432 --> 21:50.025
Not that many, no.

21:50.100 --> 21:51.745
Well it's just
that every time we talk about a car

21:51.769 --> 21:53.737
it seems to be one that you've rolled.

21:53.813 --> 21:55.916
Well I haven't talked about
that many cars though have I?

21:55.940 --> 21:58.864
But didn't you,
what was your first racing car'?

21:58.943 --> 22:00.945
- A35.
- What happened to that?

22:01.028 --> 22:02.348
That got rolled.

22:04.031 --> 22:07.626
<i>He was nothing but competitive,
against himself in</i> a <i>road car,</i>

22:07.660 --> 22:09.971
<i>it was almost at the point,
where he would start a stopwatch to see</i>

22:09.995 --> 22:13.169
<i>if he could beat
his previous time from A to B.</i>

22:35.020 --> 22:36.832
And I think it dawned on him that

22:36.856 --> 22:38.403
pretty soon he was gonna hurt himself,

22:38.482 --> 22:43.659
you can't have that many accidents
on the road and in the, on race tracks,

22:43.737 --> 22:45.799
you know you end up hurting yourself,
especially back then

22:45.823 --> 22:47.325
when the cars were lethal.

22:55.291 --> 22:57.419
<i>What got me into Formula 1
was only the fact</i>

22:57.459 --> 23:02.340
that after two or three years of racing
rather dangerously around the continent

23:02.381 --> 23:05.351
it became apparent
that I might have lots of uh... courage

23:05.426 --> 23:07.349
but nothing like enough skill
to go with it.

23:07.428 --> 23:11.308
<i>At the same time I became very friendly
with</i> a <i>young man called Piers Courage</i>

23:11.390 --> 23:13.643
<i>who was a brilliant driver.</i>

23:13.726 --> 23:15.728
And the opportunity came for Frank

23:15.811 --> 23:20.317
<i>to build a Formula 1 car
and Piers agreed to drive it.</i>

23:20.399 --> 23:24.575
And then Piers and I set off in 1969.

23:30.534 --> 23:32.832
<i>Piers Courage
was an ebullient,</i>

23:32.912 --> 23:35.256
<i>fashionable Formula 1 driver</i>

23:35.331 --> 23:38.881
<i>that captured the imagination
of everybody who loved Formula 1</i>

23:38.959 --> 23:43.214
and Piers was just, Frank's idea of
what a Grand Prix driver should be like.

23:44.214 --> 23:47.684
<i>He was just bouncy,
easily charming,</i>

23:47.760 --> 23:50.434
<i>had a beautiful wife
whom half of London was chasing.</i>

23:50.512 --> 23:52.282
Apart from being</i> a <i>great looking fella,

23:52.306 --> 23:54.400
<i>never had a hair or
a piece of clothes out of place,</i>

23:54.475 --> 23:56.523
he was always the smartest guy,

23:56.602 --> 24:01.779
buttoned down blazer, grey flannels,
Gucci shoes, he looked almost holy.

24:01.857 --> 24:02.918
<i>And I remember him
making</i> a <i>speech,</i>

24:02.942 --> 24:05.741
he had a slight sort of
English public school stammer

24:05.819 --> 24:07.867
and I remember the interviewer
saying “So Piers,

24:07.947 --> 24:09.620
"how's your car gonna go
this weekend?"

24:09.698 --> 24:12.618
"And he said, “Well I think it'll go
like an absolute b-b-b bomb actually."

24:16.664 --> 24:19.713
Hoping to go one better
than his second placing <i>last</i> year

24:19.792 --> 24:21.635
<i>was Piers Courage
in the very promising.</i>

24:21.710 --> 24:23.508
<i>Frank Williams backed De Tomaso.</i>

24:23.587 --> 24:25.635
<i>I remember last year, my right foot</i>

24:25.714 --> 24:27.591
terrific cramp in, cramp in it

24:27.675 --> 24:30.770
and also the great blisters
on my hands from the gear changing.

24:30.844 --> 24:34.144
<i>Well I kind of adored Piers
in many ways but in those days...</i>

24:34.181 --> 24:36.900
it was "Piers is wonderful,
this is my mate."

24:36.976 --> 24:38.148
I thought the world of him.

24:43.107 --> 24:45.735
<i>Piers and Frank were great together,</i>

24:45.818 --> 24:48.913
<i>they were almost made
for each other I think,</i>

24:48.988 --> 24:51.958
<i>you had Piers who was
really developing as a driver</i>

24:52.032 --> 24:56.003
<i>and Frank was really developing
as a team owner, constructor.</i>

24:58.539 --> 25:01.463
<i>Second place at Monte Carlo,
can you believe that?</i>

25:01.500 --> 25:03.798
<i>Second place the US Grand Prix,
can you believe that?</i>

25:03.877 --> 25:05.925
<i>5th at Silverstone, a great run.</i>

25:07.840 --> 25:11.686
<i>Everybody wanted to be a
racing driver and Piers was on his way,</i>

25:11.760 --> 25:13.808
<i>he'd beaten
Jackie Stewart and Jim Clark</i>

25:13.887 --> 25:16.686
and he was a really, really good driver.

25:16.765 --> 25:22.693
♪ Lark Ascending <i>J'</i>
♪ Vaughan Williams ♪

25:29.361 --> 25:33.537
And suddenly he dies in this horrendous
accident in Frank's car.

25:37.619 --> 25:39.747
<i>I</i> was <i>in</i> the race

25:39.830 --> 25:46.384
and it was a terrible accident
involving us knowing that it was Piers

25:46.420 --> 25:48.673
that had the accident
because his helmet came off.

25:54.720 --> 25:55.864
And when you heard the news,

25:55.888 --> 25:58.107
how did you hear the news?

25:58.140 --> 26:01.861
Well it was, all I will say is that it was
a major shock,

26:01.935 --> 26:04.984
I was very young, you don't
expect a shock like that

26:05.022 --> 26:06.750
and I remembered,
I went to the race organiser,

26:06.774 --> 26:09.744
a man called John Corschmidt

26:09.818 --> 26:13.698
and I said,
“John, just tell me is Piers dead?

26:13.781 --> 26:15.533
"Are you sure he's dead?"

26:15.616 --> 26:18.290
And he said I'm sure
and I said tell me that again,

26:18.368 --> 26:21.588
he told me, “He is dead Frank",
three times, I said "OK"

26:21.622 --> 26:25.126
and I got up and I had the job of telling
his wife, Piers' wife,

26:25.209 --> 26:27.007
and I'd rather not talk about that.

26:31.423 --> 26:36.224
<i>His wife, Sally,
was in a terrible state.</i>

26:36.261 --> 26:42.064
Wives in motor racing I think have had a
much tougher life than any driver has.

26:43.685 --> 26:47.110
And I remember going
to the funeral and Frank was fantastic,

26:47.189 --> 26:50.068
<i>he stood at the entrance of the church
and welcomed everybody in,</i>

26:50.150 --> 26:51.743
<i>and there were a lot of people,</i>

26:51.819 --> 26:54.197
shook hands with everybody,
thanked them for coming.

26:54.279 --> 26:56.828
And then after the ceremony
we couldn't find him

26:56.907 --> 26:59.376
and I walked back into the church, it was
deserted

26:59.451 --> 27:04.753
and Frank was standing behind a big
stone pillar, absolutely destroyed,

27:04.832 --> 27:07.335
standing
there weeping his heart out

27:07.417 --> 27:10.261
"and I said “Come
on love, let's go home."

27:10.337 --> 27:13.637
And it was like
that happy-go-lucky scene we had,

27:13.715 --> 27:15.638
<i>just dissolved like that.</i>

27:18.804 --> 27:21.148
But I know that, you know,
it wasn't really mentioned in,

27:21.223 --> 27:23.851
Piers wasn't mentioned
terribly much at home,

27:23.934 --> 27:27.029
I'm not sure dad ever,
I'm not sure how you would get over

27:27.062 --> 27:29.235
a driver dying in your car.

27:31.984 --> 27:35.079
<i>This ability of Frank to carry on,</i>

27:35.154 --> 27:39.534
<i>for me ifs fairly standard
in motor racing, knowing racing people,</i>

27:39.616 --> 27:44.042
<i>most of them only think of tomorrow,
very rarely do they look back</i>

27:44.121 --> 27:48.547
<i>and very rarely do they allow
emotion to come into their motivation.</i>

27:50.669 --> 27:52.564
<i>There was</i>
a <i>very high mortality rate,</i>

27:52.588 --> 27:54.056
<i>stupidly high</i>

27:54.131 --> 27:57.305
and it was just accepted that
you probably weren't gonna survive,

27:57.342 --> 28:01.142
I personally did not think I would
survive my Formula 1 career

28:01.180 --> 28:02.557
and the odds weren't very good.

28:05.017 --> 28:07.440
<i>On the second lap, disaster strikes,</i>

28:07.519 --> 28:11.444
<i>Von Trips loses control
but the race goes on.</i>

28:15.194 --> 28:17.788
<i>Those cars were effectively death traps,</i>

28:17.863 --> 28:19.090
<i>if you had a head-on in one of those</i>

28:19.114 --> 28:20.991
<i>they folded up
round you like an envelope,</i>

28:21.074 --> 28:22.166
You didn't get out of them.

28:24.119 --> 28:26.542
<i>The cars so readily caught fire,</i>

28:26.580 --> 28:29.049
the fuel systems in a minor impact

28:29.124 --> 28:32.719
nearly always sprung a leak
and the fires were the thing.

28:36.882 --> 28:38.805
<i>We had</i> a <i>series of deaths,</i>

28:38.884 --> 28:44.607
<i>one each weekend for four consecutive
weekends, four of our friends died.</i>

28:48.310 --> 28:52.611
<i>The ethos of Formula 1
was back then, this happens,</i>

28:52.689 --> 28:55.943
<i>ifs appalling but we, you know,
we're going to the next race,</i>

28:56.026 --> 28:58.199
like falling off a horse,
you climb back on again.

29:08.121 --> 29:09.589
So this is an article, gosh,

29:09.665 --> 29:12.259
dad did an interview with
The Times after Ayrton died.

29:14.211 --> 29:15.855
'Formula 1,
one of the most powerful figures

29:15.879 --> 29:17.096
in Formula 1 bares his soul

29:17.172 --> 29:20.551
on his star driver's death
and the revival of his team.'

29:22.135 --> 29:25.560
Dad says, “It hasn't all sunk in yet,
you <i>see,</i> the fact of Ayrton's death,

29:25.639 --> 29:28.688
the same slowness of thought
helped me get over my own accident,

29:28.767 --> 29:32.567
"I suppose that is why I'm so calm
about expressing the fact that he's dead."

29:33.772 --> 29:35.875
<i>The former
world motor racing champion,</i>

29:35.899 --> 29:38.994
<i>Ayrton Senna,
has been pronounced clinically dead.</i>

29:39.069 --> 29:42.664
<i>Senna suffered serious head injuries
when his car left the track</i>

29:42.739 --> 29:44.958
and crashed into a concrete
wall.

29:47.119 --> 29:49.793
<i>I remember at Ayrton's memorial service.</i>

29:49.871 --> 29:54.798
Mum said don't you dare cry,
she said this is not your time to be sad,

29:54.876 --> 29:56.628
she said this is not your loss.

29:58.630 --> 30:03.056
<i>Mum was a very loving lady
but she was very much of that mentality,</i>

30:03.135 --> 30:06.514
<i>stiff upper lip, exactly like dad.</i>

30:06.596 --> 30:09.475
I think they both probably
thought that emotion was weak.

30:11.852 --> 30:15.322
Well I mean it's not common
for men to show emotion,

30:15.397 --> 30:18.822
serious emotion,
maybe anger but that's about all,

30:18.900 --> 30:21.403
I mean you should never start crying
or any of that stuff.

30:21.486 --> 30:23.381
Never,
you should never start crying or...?

30:23.405 --> 30:24.827
We, I was, I was,

30:24.906 --> 30:27.910
I shed a few tears
when Piers was killed definitely.

30:27.993 --> 30:30.667
Mm... And when Ayrton,
when Ayrton died,

30:30.746 --> 30:32.248
I mean they're my responsibility.

30:32.331 --> 30:34.299
- When Ayrton died?
- Yeah sure.

30:34.374 --> 30:36.001
But, er, it was out responsibility,

30:36.084 --> 30:39.634
<i>he was in a racing car
operated by us, as was Piers.</i>

30:39.713 --> 30:42.557
Yeah it was a Williams operated car.

30:42.632 --> 30:44.885
And so how did you feel
on that day?

30:44.968 --> 30:45.968
Far from well.

31:04.696 --> 31:06.090
<i>Here he comes down the outside,</i>

31:06.114 --> 31:08.458
<i>that's a brave place to try and overtake.</i>

31:08.533 --> 31:11.377
Oh mama mia, mama mia,
oh they're gonna touch.

31:11.453 --> 31:13.706
<i>Bottas has</i> a <i>line!
They hit! They hit!</i>

31:13.789 --> 31:16.668
- <i>And Raikkonen's off this time.
- Good, fuck off.</i>

31:19.086 --> 31:23.341
We are operating on a budget of
approximately 110 million Sterling a year.

31:23.423 --> 31:26.302
And the likes of Red Bull
and Ferrari and Mercedes

31:26.385 --> 31:28.763
are operating on two
if not three times that budget.

31:28.845 --> 31:32.145
<i>So from</i> a <i>financial perspective
you could call us an underdog,</i>

31:32.224 --> 31:34.727
<i>I think that's the,
the negative connotation for me</i>

31:34.810 --> 31:38.155
<i>is it gives this sense that Williams
are weaker than anyone else,</i>

31:38.230 --> 31:42.076
but we're not, we've been through
a lot more than a lot of teams on the grid

31:42.150 --> 31:43.697
and we've always come out fighting.

31:43.777 --> 31:47.873
<i>And it's Bottas
who finishes in third place,</i>

31:47.948 --> 31:51.669
<i>superb podium for him after
the incident with Raikkonen earlier...</i>

31:51.701 --> 31:53.669
<i>Finally,</i>
a <i>podium for Williams.</i>

31:53.745 --> 31:56.874
So happy, my heart hasn't stopped
going yet, that was quite intense...

31:58.375 --> 32:02.300
Third place from Finland, Valtteri Bottas.

32:07.592 --> 32:09.737
<i>And</i> did
your mum get to see you <i>in</i> this role?

32:09.761 --> 32:13.766
No she didn't, um which...

32:16.184 --> 32:19.529
you know for me is really sad,
it's kind of heart breaking really.

32:20.480 --> 32:23.575
<i>I'm sad about that but Pm more sad that
she hasn't seen the team turn around,</i>

32:23.650 --> 32:26.529
<i>because that was
what she desperately wanted to see</i>

32:26.611 --> 32:28.659
<i>that broke her heart really at the end.</i>

32:57.559 --> 32:59.778
<i>I began to realise that
if I do want a wife</i>

32:59.853 --> 33:02.447
that she was the best
I was ever likely to find.

33:18.121 --> 33:22.171
Well it wasn't, it wasn't a posh wedding,
you know with white stuff everywhere,

33:22.250 --> 33:26.721
it was a, what do you call that thing,
a reg, a reg, registry whatever.

33:26.796 --> 33:28.232
- A registry office.
- Thank you very much.

33:28.256 --> 33:31.305
<i>I think dad had said that
he would son' the registry office out</i>

33:31.384 --> 33:34.513
and never did and would get the rings
but he didn't have any money

33:34.596 --> 33:37.145
so Mum had to borrow money from

33:37.182 --> 33:39.981
um Dave Brodie
I think it was that bought the ring.

33:40.060 --> 33:42.038
So that's it, I went there
quarter of an hour early,

33:42.062 --> 33:44.736
gave them £8.00, never got that back,
didn't expect it back.

33:44.814 --> 33:47.317
<i>It was all over in 15 minutes.</i>

33:47.400 --> 33:48.868
<i>Her parents certainly weren't there,</i>

33:48.902 --> 33:53.408
I'm not sure they approved
uh... of the match.

33:54.366 --> 33:57.620
Out we went
and I said, "Oh this a great day",

33:57.661 --> 34:01.256
let's have a celebration, I'm
gonna buy you all a spectacular lunch."

34:01.331 --> 34:03.584
Frank said,
“Not me you're not, I'm working”

34:03.667 --> 34:06.011
and he fucked off, that was it..

34:06.086 --> 34:08.589
I don't know what man
in his right mind

34:08.672 --> 34:11.641
would think that that was OK
but you know Dad did,

34:11.716 --> 34:14.469
and Dad went back to work
and Mum went to lunch

34:14.553 --> 34:17.181
and probably really
didn't think very much of it,

34:17.264 --> 34:18.982
because she was used to it by then.

34:19.849 --> 34:24.480
<i>Dad is a completely different beast
to most normal men.</i>

34:27.065 --> 34:29.159
<i>Frank from when
I first met him was,</i>

34:29.234 --> 34:31.657
<i>always seemed very fit and athletic</i>

34:31.735 --> 34:34.831
and he was forever running, every
night was a long run.

34:35.949 --> 34:38.469
<i>He ran every circuit that
we were at the race track,</i>

34:38.493 --> 34:41.292
he used to run round it
and he felt bad if he didn't,

34:41.371 --> 34:42.811
you know it was like a drug for him.

34:44.373 --> 34:47.503
<i>Frank is very,
what would be called focused,</i>

34:47.585 --> 34:49.554
<i>some people could say narrow,</i>

34:49.629 --> 34:53.132
I mean, some people
find Frank a bit unusual now

34:53.216 --> 34:58.393
and think it's because of the accident,
well it isn't, he was always very unusual.

34:59.639 --> 35:02.734
<i>In Frank
there 's</i> a <i>huge amount of repression,</i>

35:02.809 --> 35:05.028
<i>there's a huge amount of determination.</i>

35:05.061 --> 35:09.737
<i>There's an extraordinary retentive
obsessiveness.</i>

35:09.816 --> 35:11.659
<i>I suppose,
motor racing people in general</i>

35:11.735 --> 35:15.205
<i>are the most intensely competitive people,
I've ever known.</i>

35:15.280 --> 35:18.329
They're not
very mature intellectually or culturally

35:18.408 --> 35:22.288
because they neither read nor think
uh... very much except about

35:22.370 --> 35:26.500
what they actually do to which
they think in an extraordinary degree.

35:32.047 --> 35:37.224
I've never been close to Frank socially.
I mean, we've never...

35:37.260 --> 35:40.184
I don't, I don't think
we've ever been out for dinner together.

35:40.263 --> 35:44.564
He felt that anything
that involved socialising

35:44.643 --> 35:47.647
and having a drink or relaxing
was actually a waste of time.

35:59.282 --> 36:00.801
“I am addicted to motor racing",

36:00.825 --> 36:02.827
Frank Williams
declared uncompromisingly,

36:02.911 --> 36:06.211
motor racing is what matters
most in my life and then he goes,

36:06.289 --> 36:08.417
“Well I have a family which
I love very much,

36:08.500 --> 36:11.003
but they tend
to take second place to the business,

36:11.086 --> 36:13.930
"there's no question about that".

36:15.340 --> 36:18.685
But did you used to do
the family holiday type thing?

36:18.760 --> 36:19.977
Never done that, never.

36:20.053 --> 36:23.148
Oh it's too late now anyway,
never interested in that.

36:24.724 --> 36:26.818
Oh my god,
well this is embarrassing,

36:26.893 --> 36:29.612
Mum wanted a hotel
to take the three kids to

36:29.688 --> 36:32.532
and family tradition was
to have a picture of all of us

36:32.607 --> 36:34.905
on the balcony with Mum,
so that's me and Mum there,

36:34.984 --> 36:38.579
so would've been when I was
16, look at me, horrendous.

36:38.655 --> 36:43.786
So in total we went to Marbella
with mum 32 times, 32 years.

36:43.868 --> 36:45.791
How many times did your dad come?

36:45.870 --> 36:48.373
Never, not once.

36:50.458 --> 36:52.460
And that didn't bother you?
No.

36:52.502 --> 36:54.814
Mum always used to tell us,
there's no point having your father here

36:54.838 --> 36:56.715
because he would drive us all mad,

36:56.798 --> 36:59.176
so we just used to go down there
and we had a lovely time.

37:05.724 --> 37:08.523
Can you get that wheel,
fast as you can, the bottom one.

37:11.604 --> 37:13.447
Joe have we got
another wheel mounted?

37:33.084 --> 37:35.803
<i>Frank endured</i>
a <i>lot of piss taking for his efforts</i>

37:35.879 --> 37:38.098
<i>and you know
he was the poor northerner</i>

37:38.173 --> 37:40.471
<i>that didn't have a pot to piss in</i>

37:40.550 --> 37:44.896
and his cars were rubbish and, you know,
he didn't have half the parts for them.

37:46.473 --> 37:49.773
<i>Frank couldn't afford new tyres</i>

37:49.851 --> 37:54.448
and was racing
with second hand Firestone tyres I think.

37:54.522 --> 37:57.696
I wish they'd ban
tyres, there's just too many.

37:59.068 --> 38:00.379
If Ginny hadn't been there,

38:00.403 --> 38:02.906
Williams wouldn't have made it,
cause a lot of the money

38:02.989 --> 38:04.491
that kept it going was hers.

38:24.385 --> 38:28.765
I remember Ginny gave him £8.00 once

38:28.848 --> 38:31.601
<i>to go out and buy some fish and chips,
I think it was</i>

38:31.684 --> 38:35.109
and he went out and bought
eight Champion sparking plugs

38:35.188 --> 38:36.986
and never came back for three days.

38:37.065 --> 38:39.614
No I don't think my parents were
happy when they learnt

38:39.692 --> 38:44.198
that she'd sold her flat to help Frank
and to give him a bit of the money.

38:46.241 --> 38:49.120
<i>If there was
a common denominator through</i>

38:49.202 --> 38:54.959
the first decade of his relationship
with Virginia, would be penury.

39:11.432 --> 39:14.151
<i>Frank Williams' team
is at its lowest ebb</i>

39:14.227 --> 39:17.151
<i>the cars are well down the grid
in seventh and ninth places.</i>

39:26.406 --> 39:28.374
Frank came round to see me

39:28.449 --> 39:30.577
<i>"and said “Brode I can't carry on"</i>

39:30.660 --> 39:33.755
and he had a bit of paper
with debts on it and they were huge,

39:34.747 --> 39:38.377
<i>and then overnight uh... this guy
who had been creeping around with Frank</i>

39:38.459 --> 39:40.962
<i>and giving him
little bits of money, Walter Wolf,</i>

39:41.045 --> 39:43.548
<i>did something that happens
in business all the time.</i>

39:45.717 --> 39:48.140
<i>Walter bought out Frank's debt</i>

39:48.219 --> 39:52.019
<i>and took control
of the Williams Formula 1 team.</i>

39:52.098 --> 39:55.773
<i>Walter was clearly</i>
a <i>pretty clever business man</i>

39:55.852 --> 39:59.106
<i>he'd made a fortune many, many
tens of millions by himself.</i>

39:59.188 --> 40:01.532
I thought let's give this a crack.

40:01.608 --> 40:04.782
<i>But by half way through 1976,</i>

40:04.861 --> 40:09.037
<i>it was very plain to Walter
that the race team wasn't running well,</i>

40:09.115 --> 40:14.667
<i>and that Frank didn't have
the capability to turn it around.</i>

40:15.705 --> 40:17.224
And then Frank went to the factory,

40:17.248 --> 40:18.875
<i>put his key in the front door,</i>

40:18.958 --> 40:21.461
<i>it wouldn't work. Then,
the side window opened and a guy said,</i>

40:21.544 --> 40:23.939
<i>“Frank that's your things there, you can't
come into the factory,</i>

40:23.963 --> 40:25.636
<i>you're banned from the factory now”.</i>

40:25.715 --> 40:28.110
He couldn't believe it, he'd been
locked out of his own factory,

40:28.134 --> 40:31.809
it was his life, his life was in that box
and inside that factory.

40:35.308 --> 40:40.030
<i>And then six weeks later, Frank's car,
which was renamed 'The Wolf',</i>

40:40.104 --> 40:44.075
<i>went down to South America
won its first</i> race.

40:47.153 --> 40:50.703
The thing that Frank had been living for,
for all those years.

41:10.885 --> 41:13.809
One day,
Ginny phoned me up and she said,

41:13.888 --> 41:17.688
“Brode I've got a lot of problems
with Frank, he's in a fit of depression,

41:17.767 --> 41:19.940
"he hasn't got out of
his pyjamas for six weeks."

41:21.813 --> 41:25.238
<i>Sol turned up 11 o'clock
and I looked at him and I said,</i>

41:25.316 --> 41:27.034
<i>“What the fuck's going on here Frank?</i>

41:27.110 --> 41:28.657
<i>"You've got your pyjamas on."</i>

41:28.736 --> 41:34.459
"And he said “Brode, I can't quite
get my mind together about things"

41:34.534 --> 41:36.628
and I knew what was killing him.

41:56.305 --> 41:57.602
<i>I said to Frank,</i>

41:57.682 --> 42:00.119
<i>"“Look there must be some way
you can get into Formula 1 again."</i>

42:00.143 --> 42:02.121
"And he said “Well I don't know,
I don't know" he said,

42:02.145 --> 42:06.901
“but I've been thinking about it
and I might be able to get 185,000

42:06.983 --> 42:10.112
out of a Belgian beer company
called Belle-Vue

42:10.194 --> 42:14.199
<i>but we'd have to have a Belgian guy
called Patrick Néve as driver.”</i>

42:14.282 --> 42:17.456
"I said “So what?
That's the start of a new Formula 1 team."

42:17.535 --> 42:18.971
“Do you think so?“
I said, “Yeah Frank“,

42:18.995 --> 42:22.374
"I said “get out of them poxy pyjamas
and go to work, do what you're best at."

42:28.337 --> 42:30.024
We sat
at my kitchen table and I said right,

42:30.048 --> 42:32.642
"“You do a list of Formula 1 team
names and I'll do a list."

42:32.717 --> 42:35.220
And what was the name
that you came up with?

42:35.261 --> 42:38.686
Oh it was really tough,
very testing, very brain stretching

42:38.765 --> 42:41.109
but we kept it
Williams Grand Prix Operating Limited.

42:42.852 --> 42:44.747
I said
“Right I'm taking 2 days off.

42:44.771 --> 42:46.990
We're gonna go find a factory."
"Yeah!" he went.

43:07.752 --> 43:10.346
<i>It was very much
hand to mouth but uh...</i>

43:10.379 --> 43:12.222
I loved what I was doing

43:12.298 --> 43:14.458
I'm very optimistic
and I felt it would all come right.

43:16.094 --> 43:18.072
At the end of the day,
when you're a racer, you're a racer,

43:18.096 --> 43:20.224
- it's a bit of a bug.
- A bug?

43:21.766 --> 43:22.767
It gets you.

43:40.201 --> 43:43.580
<i>140,000 fans packed into Silverstone,</i>

43:43.663 --> 43:47.713
so Hamilton's on the right as we
look at it, Nico Rosburg on the left,

43:47.792 --> 43:51.171
the British Grand Prix
about to get under way,

43:51.254 --> 43:53.552
lights out, away we go
and who's it gonna be,

43:53.631 --> 43:55.776
it's a good start from the second row,
the Williams and Massa,

43:55.800 --> 43:58.895
<i>Williams out getting
both cars past both Mercedes.</i>

43:58.970 --> 44:00.739
<i>Massa leads,
Bottas trying to get</i>

44:00.763 --> 44:01.935
<i>second from Hamilton,</i>

44:02.014 --> 44:04.392
<i>Hamilton in a bit
of trouble but he's fighting back</i>

44:04.475 --> 44:08.730
<i>but we have a race on our hands,
what a start from the Williams guys.</i>

44:10.022 --> 44:12.417
- I think Valtteri is quicker.
- He is quicker, he should pass them.

44:12.441 --> 44:13.561
He should pass them.

44:13.609 --> 44:15.828
Be careful, <i>be</i> careful! And he's off!

44:15.903 --> 44:18.281
<i>Hamilton goes off in his attempts
to try and rest the lead</i>

44:18.364 --> 44:21.038
<i>and that might give an
opportunity here for Valtteri Bottas.</i>

44:21.117 --> 44:23.461
<i>Bottas goes into second place.</i>

44:24.662 --> 44:27.962
<i>And up front ifs Williams
one and two at the moment.</i>

44:35.339 --> 44:37.262
<i>Bottas comes in from the</i> race <i>lead</i>

44:37.300 --> 44:39.644
as <i>Lewis Hamilton
continues around the track,</i>

44:39.719 --> 44:43.394
<i>let's see how the stop goes
for Valtteri Bottas, ifs pretty good,</i>

44:43.472 --> 44:46.692
<i>Hamilton's already along the start
finish straight, he's alongside,</i>

44:46.767 --> 44:50.943
<i>Hamilton retakes the lead
and where does Bottas come back out?</i>

44:50.980 --> 44:55.030
<i>He comes back out behind
his team mate, Felipe Massa.</i>

44:55.109 --> 44:57.828
<i>Oh, Hamilton is pulling away in front.</i>

45:03.826 --> 45:07.046
<i>Lewis Hamilton
wins the British Grand Prix,</i>

45:07.121 --> 45:09.123
<i>he had to fight for it,</i>

45:09.207 --> 45:13.007
<i>ultimately Williams have
to settle for fourth and fifth</i>

45:13.085 --> 45:15.383
<i>but you have to feel for Williams.</i>

46:08.307 --> 46:12.312
<i>Patrick Head is
the technical genius inside Williams,</i>

46:12.395 --> 46:13.738
<i>the engineer swot who</i>

46:13.813 --> 46:16.908
<i>bestows power
on the charismatic leader.</i>

46:21.570 --> 46:24.699
When I met Patrick,
which is the best thing,

46:24.740 --> 46:26.538
apart from marrying the wife I married,

46:26.617 --> 46:28.512
was the best day
to ever happen to me in my life.

46:28.536 --> 46:30.584
<i>He was a gifted engineer.</i>

46:31.580 --> 46:37.132
<i>Patrick is</i> a <i>person who,
he doesn't suffer fools gladly...</i>

46:37.211 --> 46:38.772
Oh he's</i> a <i>bully, if he wanted it

46:38.796 --> 46:41.219
<i>and it wasn't coming
he'd bully his way through.</i>

46:41.299 --> 46:42.651
<i>A lot of people are frightened of him,</i>

46:42.675 --> 46:45.849
<i>you know he's a broad guy
and he can be quite aggressive looking</i>

46:45.928 --> 46:51.401
but his character is not one that
junior employees found comfortable,

46:51.475 --> 46:54.274
you know what I mean, they knew when
they had made a mistake.

46:54.353 --> 46:59.359
<i>I think most of
my father's forbears were military,</i>

46:59.442 --> 47:04.994
<i>one of them General Michael Head
had been a soldier under Wellington,</i>

47:05.072 --> 47:11.546
I think not wanting to fail was a very
strong motivation.

47:11.620 --> 47:16.046
This car's half a second slower
on the stop watch than the other car.

47:16.125 --> 47:17.217
Yeah.

47:24.342 --> 47:28.472
<i>The thing that was unique,
that Patrick brought to the show,</i>

47:28.554 --> 47:33.060
he was responsible
for making Formula 1 reliable.

47:33.100 --> 47:37.901
So Frank's cars
almost instantly finish races,

47:37.980 --> 47:39.482
which they hadn't been doing before

47:39.565 --> 47:42.819
and that's
where life changed for Williams.

47:45.196 --> 47:48.700
<i>The British</i> teams <i>have
kept ahead with innovative designs,</i>

47:48.741 --> 47:51.870
<i>the most recent
being the aerodynamic skirt,</i>

47:51.952 --> 47:54.080
a <i>rigid panel that scrapes
along the ground</i>

47:54.163 --> 47:56.211
<i>between the front and rear wheels,</i>

47:56.290 --> 47:59.134
<i>creating a phenomenon
called ground effect.</i>

48:01.879 --> 48:03.506
<i>For Frank Dernie a simple graph</i>

48:03.589 --> 48:07.560
<i>shows the rise in suction
under the Williams wood skirts.</i>

48:07.635 --> 48:11.356
If you remove the skirt you actually
get so little flow in this area...

48:11.430 --> 48:13.367
The thing
that really made a big difference

48:13.391 --> 48:15.689
was a fairing
along the side of the engine

48:15.768 --> 48:17.441
which allowed
the flow to remain attached

48:17.520 --> 48:20.945
<i>all the way to the back and I tested
that in a wind tunnel test</i>

48:20.981 --> 48:24.076
<i>just before Silverstone in 1979</i>

48:24.151 --> 48:28.497
and it was the biggest gain
of performance I've ever seen on a car

48:28.572 --> 48:31.416
so I rushed back from the wind tunnel
and drew the parts

48:31.492 --> 48:33.995
and we got them made so we
could use them at Silverstone.

48:36.997 --> 48:38.517
<i>I remember going out there</i>

48:38.541 --> 48:40.009
<i>and hopping in it for the first time</i>

48:40.084 --> 48:41.461
<i>and thinking bloody hell.</i>

48:41.502 --> 48:43.397
What was
the difference with the car'?

48:43.421 --> 48:47.301
It was better
it was just better.

48:47.383 --> 48:48.777
Don't start getting me,
trying to be technical

48:48.801 --> 48:50.974
because I'll look like a complete goose.

48:51.053 --> 48:55.604
<i>We went to the test
and in the morning</i>,

48:55.683 --> 48:59.313
everybody had been running and I think
the best lap time would of been uh...,

48:59.395 --> 49:04.151
I dunno 12.9 or something
by somebody and Alan went out,

49:04.233 --> 49:08.784
I remember the time absolutely,
he did a one minute 11.88 just like that,

49:08.821 --> 49:12.746
bang, and the rest of the pit lane
were doing mid 13s

49:12.825 --> 49:15.512
and it was most peculiar because
you were standing there with your thing

49:15.536 --> 49:18.380
and everybody went...
and looked down at us,

49:18.456 --> 49:20.925
they couldn't,
they just could not believe it.

49:30.801 --> 49:33.805
<i>In practice,
Alan Jones in the Saudia Williams</i>

49:33.888 --> 49:37.142
<i>has slashed an incredible
seven seconds off the record,</i>

49:37.183 --> 49:39.857
<i>and that's a lot these days.</i>

49:39.935 --> 49:41.562
<i>Alan was</i> a <i>man's man,</i>

49:41.645 --> 49:43.739
he was an Aussie,
it's all you expect from an Aussie,

49:43.814 --> 49:45.942
maybe you know big character,
strong personality,

49:46.025 --> 49:48.403
<i>took no nonsense from anybody.</i>

49:48.486 --> 49:50.909
He liked his fun, he liked to drink,

49:50.988 --> 49:54.788
<i>though I think he always had</i> a <i>bit of</i>
a <i>struggle keeping his weight down.</i>

49:54.867 --> 49:56.869
After a race
you'd nearly always see him

49:56.952 --> 49:59.876
pouring a beer down
his throat or two or three.

49:59.955 --> 50:02.434
In motor sport there's two good
reasons to have a bit of a drink,

50:02.458 --> 50:04.301
one is to commiserate
and one is to celebrate,

50:04.376 --> 50:06.925
so you're pretty safe either way
you're gonna have a beer.

50:07.004 --> 50:09.427
Two Williams <i>in</i> the first two rows,

50:09.507 --> 50:12.977
<i>the incredible veteran,
the Swiss driver, Clay Regazzoni.</i>

50:13.052 --> 50:14.696
<i>Well Clay's
not as quick as he used to be</i>

50:14.720 --> 50:16.313
<i>he's now very much
a number 2 driver</i>

50:16.388 --> 50:18.641
<i>he's number 2 to Alan Jones
in the Williams team.</i>

50:19.683 --> 50:21.651
<i>We all sort of expected Regazzoni</i>

50:21.727 --> 50:23.980
<i>to be quicker than Jones
but he never was.</i>

50:24.021 --> 50:26.194
Jones turned out
to be much, much better

50:26.273 --> 50:28.275
than any of us had realised I think.

50:28.359 --> 50:32.865
<i>Now</i> all ready
for the <i>68</i> lap British Grand <i>Prix.</i>

50:37.076 --> 50:40.751
<i>And punching through,
it's the two Saudia Williams cars,</i>

50:40.829 --> 50:44.709
<i>first into Copse Corner and
they're coming through, that's Jabouifle.</i>

50:44.792 --> 50:47.011
<i>Jean-Pierre Jabouille
is going to go through,</i>

50:47.086 --> 50:49.054
<i>he's got tremendous speed
and power here.</i>

50:49.129 --> 50:54.056
<i>510 horsepower and it is still,
Alan Jones leads now.</i>

50:54.134 --> 50:56.887
<i>When Alan took the lead
quite quickly and just disappeared,</i>

50:56.971 --> 51:00.817
Patrick and I were just counting the laps,
praying for the laps to keep reducing

51:00.891 --> 51:04.566
because it, there was a new car,
it wasn't necessarily reliable,

51:04.645 --> 51:07.524
and witnessed what was about
to be a major event for the team.

51:07.606 --> 51:10.610
<i>This became a reality.</i>

51:10.693 --> 51:14.118
And Alan Jones pulling away <i>now.</i>

51:14.196 --> 51:18.121
<i>Well I was leading very
comfortably but then all of a sudden,</i>

51:18.200 --> 51:20.419
in the rear view mirrors
I saw a hell of a lot of smoke

51:20.494 --> 51:21.721
coming out of the back of the car

51:21.745 --> 51:23.348
and I thought there was
something wrong for sure.

51:23.372 --> 51:28.378
And that is trouble for Alan Jones

51:28.460 --> 51:33.011
<i>and he, the way he's coasting,
it looks as though he's burst his engine.</i>

51:33.090 --> 51:34.818
<i>I mean I should've
hung around for the end of the race</i>

51:34.842 --> 51:37.686
but I was that pissed off
I just jumped in my car

51:37.761 --> 51:40.139
and went back to London
at about 300 mile an hour.

51:44.059 --> 51:46.437
So <i>Clay</i> Regazzoni
<i>is</i> the new leader

51:46.520 --> 51:49.524
<i>of the 33rd British Grand Prix.</i>

51:51.150 --> 51:55.906
<i>Clay Regazzoni almost home
to win the first race ever</i>

51:55.988 --> 52:01.210
<i>for the Williams team and Frank Williams
will be beside himself with joy.</i>

52:01.285 --> 52:04.255
<i>And Clay Regazzoni
goes across the line</i>

52:04.330 --> 52:07.459
<i>and he has won the British Grand Prix.</i>

52:07.499 --> 52:09.126
We were so much quicker
than anyone else,

52:09.209 --> 52:11.803
even though Clay
was nowhere near as fast as Alan

52:11.879 --> 52:14.052
<i>and of course
when Alan broke down he won.</i>

52:15.924 --> 52:17.892
We won</i> a <i>British Grand Prix,

52:17.968 --> 52:20.266
I mean you couldn't put it in a book,
it was incredible.

52:20.346 --> 52:23.850
Clay, what is
so good about this Williams car?

52:23.932 --> 52:26.151
Everything, everything
flaughsL.

52:26.226 --> 52:28.979
It was the first win
for Frank Williams in Formula 1

52:29.021 --> 52:32.025
since he started
over a decade previously.

52:32.107 --> 52:34.826
Frank Williams,
this must be the happiest day

52:34.860 --> 52:36.487
of your motor racing life.

52:36.570 --> 52:38.447
No doubt about that,
you're right yes.

52:38.530 --> 52:39.758
Frank, what were your feelings

52:39.782 --> 52:41.204
during those last few laps?

52:41.283 --> 52:43.123
Well sheer terror
that the car wouldn't finish,

52:43.160 --> 52:47.006
we'd lost Alan and I was terrified of
losing Clay but the car was very sweet.

52:47.081 --> 52:48.892
Frank we've watched you struggling,

52:48.916 --> 52:51.840
<i>if I may say so,
in motor racing since 1969.</i>

52:51.919 --> 52:53.605
<i>Frank Williams,</i>
a <i>man who's kept trying for Britain,</i>

52:53.629 --> 52:56.553
many congratulations Frank,
thank you very much.

52:58.217 --> 52:59.639
I think my parents just,

52:59.718 --> 53:01.846
after everyone had gone,
just sat there,

53:01.929 --> 53:04.102
just on the sofa
of the caravan arm in arm

53:04.139 --> 53:07.484
and just didn't want the day to end,
it was, it was surreal.

53:07.559 --> 53:09.732
So what did that feel like?

53:09.812 --> 53:15.034
Well relief I suppose, a relief,
because a lot of people would think,

53:15.109 --> 53:19.660
oh Frank, bloody Frank hasn't got a clue
what he was doing but I pressed on.

53:19.738 --> 53:23.709
For me personally I felt,
about bloody time.

53:23.784 --> 53:25.957
<i>From that moment on in the season</i>

53:26.036 --> 53:27.356
<i>I think we were totally dominant,</i>

53:27.413 --> 53:31.964
<i>we were a second or two a lap quicker
than anybody else everywhere.</i>

53:32.042 --> 53:33.937
<i>I went on and won
the next three Grand Prix's,</i>

53:33.961 --> 53:36.180
<i>I won the Dutch Grand Prix,
the Austrian Grand Prix</i>

53:36.255 --> 53:37.848
<i>and the German Grand Prix.</i>

